  <hr/>
  <h4>Non-progressive uses of <mark>faighnich</mark></h4>
  <p>When used non-progressively (i.e. in a perfective clause), <strong>faighnich</strong> generally carries the meaning <en>ask (somebody) a question</en>.</p>
  <p>Basic usage patterns are –</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Transitive, e.g. <mark>dh’fhaighnich mi ceist</mark> <en>I asked a question</en> <boxlink ref="#transitive"/></li>
    <li>Direct question, e.g. <mark>dh’fhaighnich mi, “Ciamar a tha thu?”</mark> <en>I asked, “How are you?”</en> <boxlink ref="#direct"/></li>
    <li>Indirect question, e.g. <mark>dh’fhaighnich mi ciamar a bha i</mark> <en>I asked how she was</en> <boxlink ref="#indirect"/></li>
    <li><strong>faighnich mu dheidhinn rud</strong>, e.g. <mark>dh’fhaighnich mi mu dheidhinn a’ choin</mark> <en>I asked about the dog</en> <boxlink ref="#mu"/></li>
    <li><strong>faighnich do dhuine ...</strong>, e.g. <mark>dh’fhaighnich mi do Mhàiri ...</mark> <en>I asked Mary ...</en> <boxlink ref="#do"/></li>
  </ol>
  <p>See also: <strong><a href="?gd=iarr">iarr</a></strong> <en>ask for something</en></p>

